    <h2>FAQ</h2>

    <details>
      <summary><strong>Is Termly really free?</strong></summary>
      <p>Yes. The Free tier includes one legal policy, the cookie banner with up to 10,000 banner views per month, quarterly cookie scans, and basic Google Consent Mode v2. The catch is a visible "Powered by Termly" watermark link in the banner. Removing it requires Pro+ ($20/month or ~$15/month annual).</p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><strong>Does Termly support Google Consent Mode v2?</strong></summary>
      <p>Yes — Termly is a Google CMP Partner with Gold status as of February 2026. Basic GCM v2 is available on Free and Starter; Advanced GCM v2 with full signal integration requires Pro+. The UI does not expose granular control over <code>ads_data_redaction</code> or <code>url_passthrough</code>, so advanced teams add custom GTM code on top.</p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><strong>How does Termly compare with iubenda?</strong></summary>
      <p>Termly wins on policy breadth (10 generators vs 3), US state law coverage, and phone support. iubenda wins on EU legal depth, multi-language (27 languages), and guided onboarding (personalized installation calls on every plan). For US-focused small businesses, Termly is usually the better first pick; for EU publishers or multi-language sites, iubenda is more defensible. Full comparison <a href="/iubenda-vs-termly-vs-osano.html">here</a>.</p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><strong>Will Termly work on Shopify?</strong></summary>
      <p>Technically yes, via custom HTML embed — but Termly has no native Shopify app and no Shopify API integration, a gap flagged by Enzuzo's 2026 comparison. For Shopify merchants, CookieYes or Pandectes are stronger choices.</p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><strong>Is Termly's free tier GDPR-compliant?</strong></summary>
      <p>Yes — the Free tier banner, with appropriate configuration, can satisfy GDPR consent requirements for a small site. The structural caveats: regional consent rules require Pro+ (so EU visitors see the same banner as US visitors on Free), IAB TCF 2.3 requires Pro+, and consent logs require Pro+. For a low-traffic non-monetized site, Free is genuinely adequate. For an EU programmatic publisher, it isn't.</p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary><strong>What happens if I downgrade from Pro+ to Free?</strong></summary>
      <p>Multiple verified reviewers report losing banner configuration and settings when downgrading. Plan to take screenshots of your configuration before any plan change, and assume downgrades are not lossless.</p>
    </details>

